{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_alma_ver01/data/sn96077289/00414187638/1945112301/1111.xml":{"full_text":"The MONITOR-LEADER\nMACOMB rUBLiftHING COMPANY\nlatetstT\u00dfS iSSf'LisM'.SSV'-\u2018WS\n22|nI0(<im At Mount Otam. MltfcUw.\nBUSDfEM CIRCULATION CLAMOTIED JOB PRINT IXO\nMount Cl*mono 45W\nConnecting All D*p*rtm*nt*\nMEMBER OF Til ASSOCIATED r\u00bbESS\nCLIENT 07 UNITED MMI\nsjrrsjirc\nJi \u00df i a to f M\u00bbMmb County r w SJS. \"iIES?rISS cAu*eo !2S ?*\u00a3\u2122L**\nSidg.. Dotrolt 1. _\nAFTER THE DELUGE\nReaders whose memory of the theater or movies\nspans 10 years or so may recall a play called \u2018The\nDeluge.\u201d It was the story of a group of people, a\nsmall-town group full of social, political and persona\nanimosities, who took refuge from a flood in a water\ntight basement.\nThough in temporary safety, all faced death from\nsuffocation in their unventilated refuge. And as\nbreathing became more difficult and death drew\nnearer, their enmities seemed less and less important.\nTwo by two they resolved their differences, admitted\nthe good points of their opponents\u2019 views and char\nacters, and composed their souls to meet their im\nminent fate.\nAt last the oxygen in the room was nearly ex\nhausted. Preferring quick drowning to suffocation,\none of the characters threw open the door in expec\ntation of a torrent of water. But the flood had re\nceded. And, with peril past, the bad feeling returned.\nAll departed for home as bitter as when they entered.\nThe point of that play is uncomfortably applica\nble to the present state of this country and of the\nworld. The tragic truth is that it takes the dire peril\nof war to bring out the best in men. Only in the midst\nof death and suffering, apparently, can they learn\nthe lesson of tolerance.\nSo in this war nations forgot ambition and jeal\nousy and ideological differences, and pooled their\nstrength to crush the forces of tyranny. Here at home\nworkers and employers found a way to settle dis\nputes and work together in turning out the arms that\ntoade victory possible.\nBut now that the flood of war has receded, the\ndifferences are with us again in greater intensity.\nSelfishness and stubbornness have returned. The do\nmestic front is threatened with economic war. In\nLondon, the first postwar meeting of diplomatic rep\nresentatives of the great Allies was a deadlock of\nopposing views which ended in discouragement and\ngeneral frustration.\n9 9 9\nThe knowledge that classes and nations cannot\nget along together unless they face extinction may\nnot be new. But it is shocking to have to make that\ndiscovery again. Somehow, after the bitter battle to\ncleanse the earth of the fascist scourge, everyone\nhoped that perhaps the world might become a better\nond happier place. That seemed to be the reason for\nfighting.\nYet, though we made great scientific strides dur\ning the war years, we did not keep pace in human re\nlations. Though we attained a high level of prosper\nity, we find the continuation of that prosperity en\ndangered by disputes involving a few thousands of\nour multi-million population. Though we spread the\ndoctrine of democracy far, our destinies are still\nshaped in the secret meetings of a few world states\nmen.\nAs of today, there is precious little evidence that\nthis country or the world has learned much from his\ntory\u2019s most terrible war.\nCOURTESY TO RATS\nA New York magistrate fined a man $5 for let\nting his dog kill some rats that he had caught. \u201cEven\na rat is entitled to certain courtesies,\u201d the magistrate\nsaid. \u201cIf you want to rid the neighborhood of rats,\ntrap them and drown them.\u201d\nWe agree with h's honor. If the Nazi and Jap war\nlords, and the murderous butchers of the Nazi and\nJap torture camps are assured of a trial and, at most,\na swift, clean hanging or shooting, certainly a four\nlegged rat merits equal courtesies. In fact, probably\nmore.\nTIMOR WEAPON\nThe New York Herald-Tribune reports that the\nJapanese invasion plans included the use of luminous\npainted foxes, which were to have been turned loose\nJp the dark to scare the Japs, who consider the fox\nJhi Incarnation of evil.\nJap surrender forestalled use of this weapon\ngif psychological warfare. But we shall always won\nder if skunks, with or without luminous paint,\nHvoyMn't have worked just as well.\nThe MONITOR LEADER\nPage 6\nMURAL LVvre _ i*MC> (T vOLLPeA\nmif rwePA /V\nMZHeut etc \\JflL_\nom Ht* cvepy y, elp\ni ii r a\nB(JT The 'CfeAL.\nTHREAT OF TUTueF\nAG6BE& ion N\nIs> HERE WINKIN& 1\nWMAT IFAMYtHINd. f\n\nHIM.\nIN HOLLYWOOD\nBy ERSKINE JOHNSON\nNEA Staff Correspondent\nHOLLYWOOD Freddie\nBartholomew ordered a cock\ntail, lit a cigaret and said his\nbest memory of being Holly\nwood\u2019s No. 1 juvenile star w*s\nwhen his option dropped.\nFreddie is 21 now, almost six\nfeet tall, a veteran of World War\nII and is making his stage debut\nas Marchbanks in the George\nBernard Shaw play, \u201cCandida.\u201d\nBut no one will let him for\nget that he once wore curls, star\nred in such pictures as \u201cDavid\nCopperfield\u201d and \u201cLittle Lord\nFauntleroy\u201d and earned SSOOO\na week. N\nPeople stop him on the street,\nlook at him, puzzled, and say:\n\u201cAren\u2019t you Freddie Bartholo\nmew?\u201d\nWhen Freddie says \u201cYes,\u201d the\nthe inevitable reply is:\n\u201cBut you\u2019re supposed to be a\nlittle boy!\u201d\nMovie producers say the same\nthi^g-\nAnd in the courts his parents,\nwho, he claims, left him when\nhe was three years old, are still\nfighting for a share of the money\nhe earned as a Hollywood star.\nAn injunction suit, filed by\nFreddie and his Aunt Cissy\nagainst continued harassment, is\nscheduled for hearing before\nthe United States Supreme\nCourt early next year.\nThe battle has been going on\never since Freddie first stepped\nin front of a camera, when he\nwas 10. It\u2019s no laughing matter,\nthough. Freddie said he figur\ned out the other day that he has\nspent $98,000 on attorney fees\nalone.\nWANTS TO GROW UP\nHoping to destroy the mental\npicture of him as a little boy\nin the minds of the public and\nfilm producers is his main rea\nson for playing Marchbanks in\nShaw's \u201cCandida.\u201d\n\u201cIt\u2019s the first chance I\u2019ve had\nsince I got out of the Army to\ndo a role comparable to my age,\u201d\nhe said.\n\u201cCandida\u201d will be the first\nplay of a non-profit Hollywood\ngroup which has leased a Com\nmunity Center in Westwood and\nconverted it into the Phoenix\ntheater. It will be an outlet for\nHollywood stars suffering from\ntype casting or who have not\nrecently done anything note\nworthy.\nAlthough he\u2019s quite a Holly\nwood-man-about town, dating\nsuch luscious glamor girls as\nAnn Miller and Carole Thurs\nton, Freddie says he has no\nmarriage plans. \u201cI\u2019m afraid I\u2019m\ngping to be a bachelor,\u201d he sail.\n\u201cI\u2019m even taking cooking les-\nsons.\u201d\nHe spent a year in the Army\nin Texas, six months of it in\nthe hospital. He was a Pfc.\ntraining to be a gunner on a\nB-17 when he fell from a wall\non an obstacle course and seri\nously Injured his back. After\nsix months of hospitalization,\nthe Army gave him a medical\ndischarge.\nSERGEANT LIKED HIM\nExcept for that, he said, Ar\nmy life wasn\u2019t so bad. There\nwas some snickering, he said,\nwhen word got around that Lit\ntle Lord Fauntleroy of the mov-\nNovember 23, 1945\nSpeaking of Reconversion\nies was in camp. But he quick\nly solved that.\n\u201cI mentioned that I ran\naround in Hollywood a lot with\nthe Dead End kids, which I did.\nThat immediately made me ac\nceptable.\u201d\nBut he\u2019ll never forget his\nfirst night in camp.\nHe was getting ready for bed\nwhen he was ordered to the MP\nRoving Reporters\nBY ROSETTE HARGROVE\nNEA Staff Correspondent\nPARIS To sweep a Parisian\nlady of fashion off her feet,\ndon't buy her perfume, or candy\nor flowers \u2014buy her a broom.\nA recent poll by the \u201cInstitute\nof Public Soundings\u201d has shown\nthat 91 per cent of the women\nin Paris want new brooms above\nSO THEY SAY\nThe (recent) Navy Day show\nwasn\u2019t just a party for the home\nfolks. Joe Stalin and the lead\ners of other nations were also\nspectators. The flexing of Amer\nican muscles served to remind\nthem that the United States has\nno intention to abdicate its posi\ntion as the first world power.\u2014\nAustin, Minn., Herald.\n\nThe sooner its (OPA\u2019s) un\nrealistic .-jlicies are swept away,\nthe sooner we will overcome\nthe danger of inflation by per\nmitting resumption of a peace\ntime production. Rep. Fred\nA. Hartley of New Jersey.\n\nA godly, moral America can\nnot be maintained if the young\nwomanhood of the nation is to\nmajor in liquor and minor in\neducation.\u2014The Rev. Dr. Ward\nAyer, pastor, Manhattan Calvary\nBaptist Church, New York City.\n\nThe new system adopted by\nUncle Sam for helping to edu\ncate such of his fighting boys as\nwant it is one of the finest ideas\nthat ever came out of a war,\nand wise are the lads who make\nthe most of it. Jacksonville,\nFla., Journal.\n\nThe war has proved that, for\nall practical purposes, the pro\nductivity of this country is with\nout limit. Robert C. Goodwin,\nexecutive director, U. S. Em\nployment Service.\n\nDivorces often are due to dif\nferences in temperature, as well\nas tempeVament. When tempera\ntures drop, self control drops,\ntoo, and you have a quarrelsome\nperson on your hands. Na\nthaniel Kleitman, associate pro\nfessor psychology, University of\nChicago\nIf the American people ven\ntured their capital in private in\ndustry with the same determina\ntion they financed the last two\nwars, this nation would never\nlose a depression either J.\nW. Frazer, president, Kaiser-\nFrazer Corp.\nMount Clemens, Michigan\noffice. There was a tough ser\ngeant sitting behind the desk.\n\u201cI was shaking when I walked\nup to him,\u201d Freddie said.\n\u201cThe sergeant looked me over\nfor a moment, then stood up and\nheld out his hand, saying, \u2018l\u2019ve\nliked you on the screen, Fred\ndie, and I wanted to meet you\npersonally.\u2019\nanything else. Today, of course,\nit is practically impossible to\nbuy one.\nOnly 40 per cent indicated an\ninterest in renewing their glass\nware and tableware. While most\nAmerican women want electric\nsweepers, only six per cent of\nthe French yearn for vacuum\ncleaners. Only one per cent\nbothered to mention electric\nstoves, since practical house\nwives have no illusions concern\ning the rapidity of the change\nover from wartime to peacetime\nproduction.\nPublic referendums were a\ncomparatively new venture in\nFrance before the war. It was\nnot so easy for a complete stran\nger to penetrate into French\nhomes, no matter what their\nstatus might be, and ask perti\nnent questions. The French wera\ninclined to regard this as an in\ntrusion Into their privacy.\nFour years under German oc\ncupation, however, with all ifs\ninquisitions into the lives of\nFrench citizens, have done away\nwith much of this reserve. Since\nliberation several poll services\nhave been created.\nThe object of recent poll\nwas to find out which, amonf\nthe many shortages in daily life,\ncaused most suffering. A total of\n2500 Parisians of all classes\nwere asked: \u201cWhich is the first\nimmediate improvement you\nwould want? Eighty-three per\ncent said \u201cFood.\u201d And 70 per\ncent of these were people in\nhigher income brackets. Pari\nsians are hungry and even those\nwho can afford to buy in the\nblack market do not eat well.\nAnother fact revealed was that\nwomen suffer more from hun\nger than men do.\nSHOES STILL SCARCE\nWhat is the next most press\ning need on the Parisians\u2019 list?\nUnderwear \u2014according to 85 per\ncent of the answers, closely fol\nlowed by 80 per cent who need\nsuits and dresses more than un\nderwear. Stocks of household\nlinen are pretty well exhausted,\nin 89 per cent of Parisian fami\nlies. More than 55 per cent need\nworking clothes.\nThe acute footwear shortage\nshows no signs of improvement\nat any rate in the next six\nmonths. Thus 89 per cent of Pa\nrisians urgently need both shoes\nand slippers. Only 21 per cent\nmentioned children\u2019s clothes\nThis is easily explained by the\nfact that there is always the pos\nsibility of making children\u2019s\nclothes out of an adult's ward\nrobe and there are- countless\nparents who have sacrificed\ndresses or suits for their chil\ndren.\nBEHIND THE SCENES\nIN WASHINGTON\nBy PETER EDSON\nNEA Washington Correspondent\nWASHINGTON\u2014Top govern\nment economists are now pretty\nwell out on a limb with predic\ntions of eight million unemploy\ned by next April.\nThis is the pessimistic side of\nthe picture. It is based on the\nbelief that everything is going\nto pot, following the pattern of\nthe postwar depression of 1922.\nIt takes discouragement from\nthe belief that employers are\nholding back on opening up new\njobs until government wage and\nprice policies are settled, that\nstrikes will increase, that wage\ncuts will reduce purchasing pow\ner, and that everyone will hang\nonto his savings for food and\nshelter instead of spending for\nnew autos, refrigerators and\nsuch things, to create a postwar\nboom.\nThe other side of the picture is\nmore optimistic. It is based on\nthe belief that what lies ahead\nis merely a little readjustment\nrecession, following the pattern\nof 1919. It takes encouragement\nfrom the belief that as soon as\nbusiness gets squared away and\nbegins operating under lower\ntaxes in 1946, there will be a big\npick-up and things will begin\nto get good. Under this line of\nthinking, there won\u2019t be any\neight million unemployed next\nspring.\nIn support of this latter view,\nit must be admitted that from\nthe V-days up to Nov, 1, the\nQUESTIONS\nAND\nANSWERS\nQ \u2014Are oranges being dehy\ndrated successfully?\nA\u2014They are. A 90 pound\ncrate can be reduced to seven\npounds of powder.\n\nQ \u2014Who won the first nation\nal school safety poster contest\nconducted recently by the\nAmerican Automobile Associa\ntion?\nA\u2014Charles R. Dickinson, Jr.,\nCass Technical High School, De\ntroit. First prize was a SSO War\nBond and SIOO cash.\n\nQ \u2014What colonies does Great\nBritain hold in the West Indies?\nA\u2014The Bahamas, Barbados,\nTrinidad, Jamaica, British Gui\nana, British Honduras and the\nLeeward and Windward Is\nlands.\n\nQ \u2014What is the state flower of\nOklahoma?\nA\u2014Mistletoe.\n\nQ \u2014What is the population\nand area of Vatican City?\nA\u2014 Population, last census\n(1932), 1025; area, 13 acres.\n\nQ \u2014What is the greatest ocean\ndepth registered?\nA\u2014Near the island of Minda\nnao, 35,400 feet has been record\ned.\n\nQ \u2014What are the spiritual tit\nles of the Pope?\nA\u2014Vicar of Christ, Successor\nof St. Peter, Bishop of Rome,\nArchbishop and Metropolitan of\nthe Roman Province, Primate of\nItaly, Patriarch of the West, Su\npreme Pontiff of the Universal\nChurch.\n\nQ \u2014How much tax do owners\nof motor trucks pay in the Unit\ned States?\nA\u2014Nearly $500,000,000 an\nnually. There are more than 5,-\n000,000 in operation, more than\nin all the rest of the world com\nbined.\n\nQ \u2014What is the largest British\nairplane in operation?\nA\u2014The 58-ton, four-motored\nShetland flying boat. Larger\nthan the U.S. Martin \u201cMars.\u201d it\nhas a range of 4,650 miles at 184\nmiles an hour.\na\nQ \u2014What is the significance\nof Maritime Day, celebrated on\nMay 22?\nA\u2014lt was created by Con\ngress in 1933 to commemorate\nthe departure of the SS Savan\nnah from Savannah. Ga., in\n1819 on the first transocean\ncrossing using steam propulsion.\n\nQ \u2014Which is the greater, the\npolar or equatorial radius of the\nearth?\nA\u2014The latter. 3,963.34 stat\nute miles against $3,949.99 stat\nute miles.\n\nQ \u2014What is the derivation of\nthe name \u201cCecilia?\u201d\nA\u2014lt comes from the Latin,\nand means gray-eyed, or blind.\n\nQ \u2014What was the extent of\naerial bombardment damage to\nthe Ruhr industrial area of Ger\nmany during the war?\nA\u2014More than 50 per cent of\nall the bud sgtfr IV- 1 Hint\nall the buildings in the 14 prin\ncipal cities were completely des\ntroyed.\nshock of unemployment has\nbeen a darn sight less than most\nof the prophets of doom have\nbeen wailing. This esn be seen\nbest in reports on state unem\nployment compensation figures.\nIt is impossible to chart these\nfigures and project them to\nshow what the situation will be\nnext spring.\nIt is pretty well established\nthat end of the war and cancel\nlation of war contracts threw\nover six million workers out of\njobs.\nMANY SHIFT TO\nPEACETIME JOBS\nThere are no accurate data on\nwhat has happened to these six\nmillion ex-war workers, says\nEwan Clague, director of the\nBureau of Unemployment Se\ncurity. But there are some\npretty good indications. They\nshow that three million shifted\nto peacetime jobs immediately.\nTwo million more have filed\nclaims for umemployment com\npensation. One million are un\naccounted for. They may be\ntaking vacations or they may\nhave retired from the labor\nmarket.\nIn the first 10 days after VJ\nday, 650,000 laid-off war plant\nworkers filed claims for job in\nsurance. The last week in Aug\nust it was 496,000. First week\nin September it was 296,000.\nFirst week in October it was a\nlittle above 200,000, and the\nfirst week in November it was\nunder 200,000.\nIt is not safe to say this marks\nthe downturn in the tide of re\nconversion unemployment, says\nClague. The trend may be re\nversed in coming weeks. But\nas of mid-October, when the r e\nwere only 1,750,000 ex-war\nworkers registered for unem\nployment insurance, 10 per\ncent, or between 175,000 and\n200,000, were being dropped off\nthe rolls because they had found\nnew jobs. In other words, they\nwere dropping off the unem\nployment compensation rolls al\nmost as fast as they were being\nadded.\nRETURNING VETERANS\nA QUESTION\nIf this reasoning is correct. It\nmeans that the whole problem\nahead depends on what happens\nto the returning veterans. To\ndate, 2,225,000 service men and\nwomen have been demobilized.\nWhat has happened to them is\nharder to determine than with\nthe civilian ex-war workers.\nMany of the vets are taking long\nrests before going back to\nwork.\nBut the surprising fact is that\nas of October 1, only 99,000 were\ndrawing unemployment benefits\nin the form of readjustment al\nlowances under the GI bill of\nrights, and the new applications\nfor benefits were coming in at\nthe rate of only 7000 a week.\nThat would indicate that the\nvast majority of the 300,000\nservice people now being de\nmobilized each week are find\ning jobs.\nDemobilization is now only\none-third complete, with four\nmillion more vets plus two mil\nlion government workers to go\nby midsummer. It is normal to\nexpect that when a veteran\ncomes back he may bump a civ\nilian out of a job. That factor\ncould conceivably increase the\nload on civilian unemployment\ncompensation.\nWhether the eight million un\nemployed is an April fool pre\ndiction depends finally on how\nfast industry can open up new\njobs in building, the auto indus\ntry, agriculture, the service\ntrades and so on\u2014all of which\nnow show a potential of em\nploying four or five million more\nworkers.\nFinnish Statesman\nHORIZONTAL\n1,5 Pictured\nFinnish\nstatesman\nit Church laws\n13 Bar science\n16 Art (Latin)\n16 Armed Zulus\n16 Soft drink\n19 Greek letter\n20 Herb\nS3 Be seated\nS3 Stem\n25 Tangle\n37 Dutch painter\n29 Follow\n32 Grandchild\n(Scot)\n33 Anent\n34 Rhode Island\n(sb.)\n35 Senior (ab.)\n36 Foundation\n38 Sicker\n40 Hawaiian\nwreath\n41 Letter\n42 Consumed\n44 Continent\n49 Insect\n82 lifer\n88 Rosier\n84 Put on\n88 Hung over\n88 Latest\n\u2022lltn\na Simple\nVERTICAL\n1 Hearing\ntWtSu\nMcKENNEY ON\nBRIDGE\nBy WILLIAM E. McKENNEY\nAmerica\u2019s Card Authority\nOffhand, I suppose one might\nsay that New York has the best\ngroup of bridge players. How\never, Philadelphia can produce\nas many, and possibly more fine\nplayers at a tournament, than\nany other city. Certainly the\nbest players from both these\ncities will compete in the forth\ncoming national tournament.\nSimon (Skippy) Becker of\nPhila delpbia made a nice bid at\nthe Eastern Pennsylvania tour-\nAKQJ 102\nVQ4\nIS\nAAKSS\n\u25a0\u2022chtr p-w\nAA94 A875\nVK962 W E 1087 5\n984 Q J 10 7\nA io 8 4 Dttlar 2\nA 8\nAll\nV AJS\n\u2666A K 5\nAQJ972\nDuplicate\u2014Neither vul.\nSooth Weet North East\n1A Pass 4N T Pom\nSV Double ON T. Pass\nIt\nnarrtfent at Reading, where he\nwon the pair event with Joseph\nDavis. It is one you might bear\nin mind when you are compet\ning against the Blackwood con\nvention.\nI did not particularly like\nNorth\u2019s jump to four no trump,\nbut that is what he did, and\nSouth correctly bid five hearts\nshowing two aces.\nBecker based his double on\nthe inference that one of South\u2019s\ntwo aces was very likely the ace\nof hearts. Therefore he felt\nthat a heart opening would help\nto defeat the slam contract to\nwhich North-South appeared to\nbe headed, as he (Becker) held\nthe ace of spades.\nNorth's jump to six no trump\nwas a wild stab In the dark, but\nBecker\u2019s reasoning was correct.\nWith a diamond opening, six no\ntrump was cold, but with a\nheart opening the hand went\ndown.\nBARBS\nIt seems that the popular way\nto celebrate getting the old auto\nfixed up is to have a big blow\nout.\n\nA henpecked husband Is a\nman who has his nerve in his\nwife\u2019s name.\n\nA man who is willing to do\nnothing has a hard time land\ning work because all of the\nhigh salaried jobs are taken.\n\nToo many people do a poor\njob of growing old because they\nwon\u2019t take their time about it.\n\nThere\u2019s a villain in every\nmovie. He sticks gum under the\nseats.\n\nThe flask-toting rooter misses\nchances to cheer the home team\non. Nip, nip, hooray!\n\nIt\u2019s funny how many people\nspend all day getting out of a\nmorning's work.\n\nAn osteopath says people\neventually will forget how to\nwalk. Not as long as second\nhand cars keep breaking down.\n\nCake and pie recipes ought to\nread, \u201cadd a cup or so of bor\nrowed flour.\u2019*\n\nThe difference between suc\ncess and failure is the difference\nbetween living because you\nwant to and because you must.\nINefitiv.\n4 Upon*\nSindian\n6 Os the ear\n7 Beholdl\n8 South latitude\n(ab.)\nOBrowpa\n10 African desert\n11 Head gear\n12 Courtesy title\n148tffl\n17 Manganese\n(ab.)\n20 Loss of\nmemory\n21 He died in\n24 Ragle's neat\n26 Senile\n27Ctry\n28 Beverage\nOOAngky\n31 Stray\n37 Coat part I\n39 He was a 1\nIn his country\n42 Tree I\n48 War god\n45 Worry\nFT ifcfc iLJBfc IU\n41 Mil IJr\nAmww t# Ffsstses r\u2014it\n46 Was carried\n47 That one\n48 Is able\n50 Organ of\nsmell\n51 Explosive\n56 Spanish\narticle\n67 Sun god\nSOTJrpe moasue\n60 Us","height":"30897","width":"23367"}}
